The paper discusses a method to extract citation counts for dissertations, which are typically found in digital libraries and repositories. The paper also compares the Google Scholar citation counts with Mendeley reader counts, which are both related to scholarly impact. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.DL (Digital Libraries), followed by cs.IR (Information Retrieval) and cs.CY (Computers and Society). The paper may also be relevant to cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) and cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) as they both deal with impact assessment and scholarly communication.
